  "prompt": "What does it mean when ETA case number shows \"Certified\" in iCERT?",
  "response": "In the iCERT system (which is the online portal managed by the U.S. Department of Labor for processing PERM and other labor certification applications), when an ETA case number shows **\"Certified\"**, it means that the **labor certification application** (PERM or other type) has been approved by the Department of Labor (DOL). \n\nHere\u2019s what this status typically implies:\n\n1. **Approval of Labor Certification**: The employer's application to certify that there are no qualified U.S. workers available for the position and that hiring the foreign worker will not adversely affect the wages and working conditions of U.S. workers has been approved.\n\n2. **Next Steps**: With the certified labor certification, the employer can proceed to the next stage of the immigration process. For example:\n   - In the PERM process, the employer can file an **I-140 Immigrant Petition** with USCIS on behalf of the foreign worker.\n   - The foreign worker may then proceed with their green card application based on the approved labor certification.\n\n3. **Validity**: A certified labor certification is typically valid for **180 days** from the date of certification. The employer must file the I-140 petition within this period; otherwise, the certification will expire.\n\n4. **Finality**: Unless there are issues of fraud or misrepresentation, the DOL's certification is final and cannot be appealed or revoked by the DOL.\n\nIf you see the status as **\"Certified\"**, it\u2019s a positive outcome, and the employer and foreign worker can move forward with the next steps in the immigration process.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
